On the scene came Christ The Lord, not with peace but with a sword.
He startled hearts grown comfortable, he shattered every cord.
His message, fierce and urgent, split the silence of the land;
He challenged every boundary, and forced the trembling hand.

He spoke of love, but love that burns, and justice sharp and clear;
He called for change that shakes the earth, and casts away all fear.
The sword he brought was truth revealed, a rift through every lie;
A call to rise, to sacrifice, to live and dare and die.

So Christ arrived with sword in hand, dividing night from day;
To stir the soul, to wake the world, to show a brighter way.

Farewell, thou child of my right hand, and joy;  
A sudden hush where laughter used to be.  
Gone is the morning’s brightness, now destroyed;  
A shadow falls across the family tree.  

Yet in the empty spaces of my days,  
Your gentle spirit gathers, soft and near.  
No time or tide can wash your love away—  
I hold you close, though you are not here.  

Farewell, my treasure, carved from hope and pain;  
In memory’s garden, you shall bloom again.
